data.enText: a calm and confident manner with control of your feelings or behaviour
the ability to move or stand in an elegant way with good control of your body

data.chText: 保持（某种姿势）；抓紧；使稳定
data.enText: to be or hold sth steady in a particular position, especially above sth else

data.chText: 老鹰在半空中盘旋，准备俯冲。
data.enText: The hawk poised in mid-air ready to swoop.

data.chText: 他稳定住自己，以发动最后攻击。

data.hoverText: 动词+名词短语+带to的不定式

data.enText: He was poising himself to launch a final attack.

data.chText: 她把标枪握稳，然后投了出去。
data.enText: She poised the javelin in her hand before the throw.

tr: great coolness and composure under strain
a cgs unit of dynamic viscosity equal to one dyne-second per square centimeter
the viscosity of a fluid in which a force of one dyne per square centimeter maintains a velocity of 1 centimeter per second
a state of being balanced in a stable equilibrium
cause to be balanced or suspended
prepare (oneself) for something unpleasant or difficult

example: The bird poised for a few moments before it attacked

value.def: If someone has poise, they are calm, dignified, and self-controlled.

example.ex: What amazed him even more than her appearance was her poise...
example.tran: 她的容貌让他惊叹，而更让他惊讶的是她的沉着。

example.ex: It took a moment for Mark to recover his poise.
example.tran: 马克过了一会儿才恢复镇静。

value.def: Poise is a graceful, very controlled way of standing and moving.

example.ex: Ballet classes are important for poise and grace...
example.tran: 芭蕾课对培养优雅的姿仪非常重要。

example.ex: Even when he moved he did so without poise.
example.tran: 他就连走起路来也姿势难看。
